WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.680
 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture

00:00:01.680 --> 00:00:04.640
 on continuous analog computing.

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:07.320
 So there's a lot of things I'm gonna show you.

00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:08.640
 They don't matter too much

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:10.880
 'cause the real overall theme here is

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:13.760
 continuous means that these are devices

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:16.740
 that have sort of knobs or gears or sliders

00:00:16.740 --> 00:00:20.900
 that use physical movement to approximate a computation.

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:22.120
 The key to these devices,

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:24.660
 like this device we'll play with in a little bit,

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:28.260
 is the carefully printed scales that are on these devices.

00:00:29.340 --> 00:00:32.400
 Because as you move them, you are reading from the scales,

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:35.520
 you're inputting data into them using the scales

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:38.280
 and you're taking data out of them using the scales.

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:41.800
 And so that's a critical element of these,

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:46.080
 is that the scales are very, very carefully calibrated

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:47.080
 and built.

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:48.900
 But then once you've got those scales,

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:50.800
 the device is pretty simple to operate.

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:52.560
 That's the basic idea.

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:56.040
 Now the oldest known continuous analog computer

00:00:56.040 --> 00:00:57.840
 is the Antikythera mechanism.

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:02.240
 It was found in a shipwreck around Greece

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:04.360
 near an island called Antikythera.

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:07.840
 And it uses gears to model the known solar system.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:10.120
 It can model the sun and the moon and the earth,

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:12.460
 Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn.

00:01:12.460 --> 00:01:15.560
 And it doesn't just think of it as 24 hours a day,

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:17.280
 365 days a year.

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:19.460
 That actually is just a simplification.

00:01:19.460 --> 00:01:21.040
 That's why we have leap years.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.080
 It can model the more complex cycles

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:27.560
 where 19 year cycles and a 76 year cycle and a 223 cycle.

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:30.160
 And a lot of people want to think of this thing

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:33.360
 as quite mystical, like holy mackerel.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:35.480
 People build a computer this long ago,

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:38.360
 and it turns out it's not that all complex.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:44.120
 But it had this idea of such an early, such a precise device,

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:49.960
 so much data, solar, star, and planet observation

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:52.220
 that went into this, that it really

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:55.640
 has this air of mystery and mysticism about it.

00:01:55.640 --> 00:01:58.280
 And this led to a movie called "Indiana Jones

00:01:58.280 --> 00:01:59.320
 and the Dial of Destiny."

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:05.440
 And the basic idea was, is that in addition to the 24/7, 365

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:07.240
 cycle, there's an even longer cycle.

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:09.520
 And at some point, this dial of destiny,

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:11.440
 which is an Antikythera mechanism,

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:15.720
 will predict when a time portal will open and close.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.280
 So you can go back in time sort of for one 24 hour period.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:22.920
 And that's pretty fun.

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:27.120
 And I love the movie, and I love the Antikythera mechanism.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:30.800
 They've made replicas of the Antikythera mechanism

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:33.640
 in various museums.

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:35.160
 But here's the interesting thing.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:36.920
 They're not very mystical at all,

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:40.360
 because you can buy one on Amazon.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:41.760
 And I did.

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:46.920
 So here is a cheap imitation Antikythera mechanism.

00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:49.840
 And you can see here that it has gears,

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:52.480
 and it has very careful scales.

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:55.080
 It's got these scales for both the sun

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:56.760
 scale and the moon scale.

00:02:56.760 --> 00:02:59.240
 So the phases of the moon, whether it's

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.320
 a full moon, a new moon, et cetera.

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:05.800
 And so the idea is, the sizes of these gears

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:09.520
 is carefully calculated by the data in the solar system.

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:14.320
 And when you spin it around, there we go,

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:18.720
 you can see that the gears are keeping everything in control.

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:21.960
 And you can then stop and then read.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:24.320
 So we're now in the middle of summer.

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:26.560
 And it's a particular day, and the moon

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:28.240
 is in a particular spot.

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:33.440
 And so that is a very simple Antikythera mechanism.

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:37.960
 Now, ironically, the way I'm holding this,

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:41.600
 we have this simple notion that we were taught in school

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:46.320
 about the solar system, that it says flat plane, like this.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:49.560
 And all the planets are kind of in one plane.

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:52.320
 But it's not true, because it just turns out

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:56.120
 that the whole sun is moving.

00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:59.800
 So it's like the sun is moving through the Milky Way.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:04.120
 And I don't know if I got that very well, but there you go.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:06.320
 The sun is moving through the Milky Way.

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:10.040
 So I couldn't get licensing for a really good video of this,

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:12.840
 but there are some really pretty videos called--

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:15.400
 you can go search or look for AI.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:18.000
 Tell me about the actual motion of the Earth

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:19.840
 through the Milky Way galaxy.

00:04:19.840 --> 00:04:22.760
 Oh, and by the way, the notion that the sun

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:25.200
 was the thing around which everything was rotating,

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:30.360
 the heliocentrism, got Nicholas Copernicus in trouble in 1543.

00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:34.000
 And you can Google that as well.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.080
 Now, I want to talk a little bit about modern, continuous,

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:38.160
 analog devices.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:40.200
 One's not quite so modern.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:42.040
 It's been replaced by the Hampton calculator,

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:43.400
 which is the slide rule.

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:47.040
 And the other is a wind calculator for airplane pilots

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:50.280
 that uses a circular calculator to do trigonometry

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:53.000
 and Pythagorean theorem, mostly to compensate

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:54.760
 for wind direction on an airplane.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.800
 We'll talk about both of them.

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:58.680
 So let's start talking about a slide rule.

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:00.480
 So a slide rule is a device.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:04.920
 Again, all analog continuous devices have a scale on them.

00:05:04.920 --> 00:05:08.680
 And this is a really tiny, very fine, highly accurate scale

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:11.480
 that maps numbers to their corresponding logarithm.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:13.680
 So you could think of this entire device

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:17.720
 as a function mapping x to log x.

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:21.120
 And then what you do is you move this back and forth.

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:24.920
 And you can affect doing addition and subtraction.

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:27.200
 And then you can add logarithms.

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:30.040
 And that's the same as multiplying and subtracting

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:32.720
 logarithms is the same as dividing,

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:35.560
 as long as you can keep track of the exponent.

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:38.200
 And so if you go back in the '50s and the '60s,

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:40.320
 or if you watch the movie Hidden Figures,

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:43.720
 you will see that everyone is carrying around a slide rule.

00:05:43.720 --> 00:05:45.320
 And when I watched that movie Hidden Figures,

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:47.120
 I absolutely loved that detail

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:48.800
 of everyone having a slide rule,

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:50.120
 'cause that's really what it was like

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:51.960
 to be an engineer back in those times,

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:54.440
 'cause we didn't have hand calculators.

00:05:54.440 --> 00:05:58.160
 All we had was a slide rule to do our multiplication for you.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:01.680
 And I built an online slide rule that you can play with.

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:05.160
 So the next thing I wanna talk about

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:08.400
 is computing wind correction in an airplane.

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:12.120
 So if you take an airplane, it spins a propeller

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:15.560
 and it goes through the sky at a certain speed.

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:17.480
 And you can point it in any direction you want,

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:19.800
 and then you go up and you fly for a while,

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:22.080
 point it wherever you want, and then you come back down.

00:06:22.080 --> 00:06:24.260
 And if you know the distance and you know the speed,

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:25.560
 you can figure out about how long

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:28.000
 it's gonna take an hour and 15 minutes to get there.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:29.760
 But there's a problem.

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:30.860
 There's wind.

00:06:30.860 --> 00:06:33.000
 So let's just say I wanna fly this little airplane

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.960
 from me to you, let me grab it better.

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:37.440
 I wanna fly this airplane from me to you.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:41.040
 And you're 100 miles away-ish,

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:43.560
 and it's gonna take me an hour to get to you.

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:46.240
 But what if there is a wind

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:49.120
 that's coming from this direction, okay?

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:51.840
 So the problem is if I aim at you,

00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:53.680
 the wind is just gonna push me,

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:55.240
 and I'm not gonna get to you.

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:56.920
 And not only it'll take me more than an hour,

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:59.040
 'cause the wind is actually not just moving me,

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:00.560
 but slowing me down.

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:02.540
 So when that hour is done,

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:06.720
 I will not be where you're at.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:08.520
 I'll be lost.

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:12.800
 And so a big part of teaching us pilots

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:16.720
 is to know how to adjust what we call the crab angle,

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:19.120
 which is to aim the airplane

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:20.940
 in a different direction than we wanna go

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:23.440
 to compensate for the wind that's pushing us.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:24.920
 For our airplane goes 100 knots,

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:26.800
 which is like roughly miles per hour,

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:29.560
 and we wanna go west 270 degrees,

00:07:29.560 --> 00:07:33.020
 and the wind is out of 300 degrees at 15 knots.

00:07:33.020 --> 00:07:37.600
 If we fly west, the wind will both slow us down.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:40.120
 So where should we actually point the plane

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:42.580
 to actually have a ground track that is west,

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:44.360
 and what is our effective speed

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:47.160
 so we can calculate how long it's gonna take us

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:48.760
 to get there, okay?

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:53.560
 So one way to do this is the Law of Sines.

00:07:53.560 --> 00:07:55.480
 Everybody knows the Law of Sines.

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:59.480
 The Law of Sines says that the ratio

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:03.480
 of the sine of an angle to the sine,

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:05.720
 the length of the side opposite that angle

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:09.000
 is the same for triangles, most triangles.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.640
 Turns out if the angles get too big or too small,

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:13.920
 you've gotta kinda transform a little bit.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.320
 So it's not too easy.

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:18.480
 But there is math that tells you

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:22.280
 how to calculate this effect of wind on an airplane,

00:08:22.280 --> 00:08:24.640
 both in terms of changing ground speed

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:26.920
 and direction you have to go.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:29.560
 And so you'll see we have a head wind,

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:31.680
 the first one, where the wind is coming

00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:33.360
 from our right and in front of us.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:35.080
 Then we have a side wind

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:36.640
 where it's just coming from our right.

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:37.800
 And then we have a tail wind

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:41.200
 which is coming from our right and behind us.

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:42.760
 And you have to calculate all those things

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:45.240
 'cause your plane may speed up or slow down

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.720
 and it might affect where you have to point the plane.

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:51.120
 And I provide there some simple,

00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:53.920
 beautiful mathematics in Python.

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:55.420
 And it's actually more complex than that

00:08:55.420 --> 00:08:57.800
 because not every triangle works this way

00:08:57.800 --> 00:09:00.200
 and so you have to adjust your triangle sometimes.

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:03.480
 So our airplane goes west and we wanna go 270 degrees,

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:07.000
 the wind is out of the northwest at 300 degrees and 15 knots.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.800
 The answer is we're going to fly a heading of 274 degrees

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:13.560
 and calculate our distance

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:16.800
 based on a westward ground speed of 87 knots.

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:21.200
 That's the answer which we could get through trigonometry.

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:24.120
 But we really don't want to have pilots

00:09:24.120 --> 00:09:27.700
 running trigonometry in a plane maybe at night.

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:30.160
 They get a call on a radio and it says,

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.200
 the wind is no longer out of 300 at 15 knots,

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:37.960
 it's out of 243 at 80 knots or whatever.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:39.280
 And you gotta recalculate where you're at

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:42.200
 'cause you've gone a certain distance,

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:45.200
 you gotta recalculate where you're gonna point the plane,

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:46.360
 all those things.

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:51.120
 And as interesting, as complex as the trigonometry

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:54.320
 is we really don't want pilots

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:59.320
 to be doing sign computations in the darkness.

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:00.880
 And they didn't have hand calculators.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:04.800
 And so part of the reason that pilots

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:07.760
 still train on this stuff

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:12.040
 is that we don't want to depend too much on technology.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:13.800
 I literally have on my cell phone

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:19.120
 an application that can tell me where the weather is,

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:21.920
 where I'm at, how high I am, how fast I'm going,

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.280
 all the other planes in the sky, et cetera.

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:25.600
 And that's great.

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:27.800
 But part of piloting is not depending

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:28.960
 on technology too much.

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:31.440
 You need to be able to just fly the plane

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:33.480
 if somehow the technology fails you.

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:37.300
 And so this is still taught in pilot training.

00:10:37.300 --> 00:10:40.760
 It's still tested in your pilot exam.

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:44.120
 And it's an interesting thing in the notion

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:45.520
 that this is something that came from

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:47.300
 probably the 30s or the 40s.

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:51.600
 It's a really cool analog computer

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:54.220
 that we learn today as pilots.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:56.440
 So let me show you how this works.

00:10:56.440 --> 00:10:58.200
 We're gonna do a simple calculation

00:10:58.200 --> 00:11:02.680
 for airspeed correction and heading correction on an E6B.

00:11:02.680 --> 00:11:07.120
 Our problem is a 15 knot headwind.

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:09.600
 So we put our little hole at 100

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:13.360
 and then we go up 15 knots, 110, 115,

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:16.280
 and put a mark right at the 15 knot mark.

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:19.000
 And the direction the wind is coming from

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.140
 is 300 degrees.

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:22.880
 We're flying 300 degrees.

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:26.180
 We would have a headwind of 15 knots,

00:11:26.180 --> 00:11:27.760
 which would slow us down.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.000
 Our plane goes 100 knots,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
 so it'd be going 85 on the ground.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:33.760
 But that's not where we wanna go.

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:35.920
 We don't wanna fly to 300.

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:38.240
 We wanna fly to 270.

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:40.400
 Now, as we're moving this,

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:42.280
 in a sense this analog calculator

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:45.080
 is doing a bunch of sines and cosines,

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:47.600
 Pythagorean theorem, but we don't care.

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:48.640
 We're just moving it.

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:52.280
 It is a physical thing and it is recalculated.

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:55.680
 So the first thing we do is we put the heading

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:59.260
 that we intend to fly up there at the true index.

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:03.440
 So we're gonna fly 270 or westerly.

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:07.320
 Then what we've got to do is we've got to take the point,

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:10.800
 this point here, and we gotta move it down to 100 knots

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:12.760
 'cause that's how fast our plane is.

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:17.200
 And you can see that the headwind is slowing us down.

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:20.240
 So now we've compensated for the headwind.

00:12:20.240 --> 00:12:23.740
 And so if you look, our plane normally goes 100 knots,

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:27.120
 but with this particular wind, this 15 knot wind,

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:29.540
 it's gonna do 86, 87 knots.

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:33.920
 And we also have to figure out what we call the crab angle,

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:37.720
 which is the way we have to fly to go to the west

00:12:37.720 --> 00:12:39.600
 to compensate for the wind.

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:42.200
 So we have to add four degrees,

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:46.680
 and that is one, two, three, four.

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:50.240
 So now we have, without doing any mathematics,

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:53.040
 nothing but manipulating a physical device,

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:55.440
 we have calculated the actual airspeed

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:58.840
 and the compensation that we need to do

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:02.940
 for a wind of 15 knots out of a heading of 300

00:13:02.940 --> 00:13:05.840
 in order to maintain a heading of 270.

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:08.500
 The point of this is not to teach flying.

00:13:08.500 --> 00:13:12.800
 It is the fact that a carefully engineered,

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:15.420
 carefully calibrated physical analog device

00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:18.920
 can do beautiful calculations that are graphical in nature

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:20.840
 and frankly, very easy to use.

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:21.840
 Don't need a lot of training.

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:25.880
 You just have to know how to rotate and move and read

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:29.340
 using things like sliding, rotating scales, gears.

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:30.920
 You can even do crazy calculations

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:34.380
 with things like water and pulleys.

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:36.800
 So this kind of concludes our brief look

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:38.920
 at analog computing devices.

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:42.440
 Up next, we're gonna talk about digital computing devices.

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:45.460
 And digital computing devices are things

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:47.560
 that make clicking noises.

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:49.440
 They're still physical devices.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:51.360
 They're, by definition, analog,

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:53.160
 but they have two states,

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:56.680
 and they are stable when in each of the states,

00:13:56.680 --> 00:13:59.520
 and we can have input to change their state.

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:04.380
 So a pen is kind of a classic physical digital device.

00:14:04.380 --> 00:14:07.380
 (upbeat jazz music)

